{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cb6ed51d-e20c-4af3-bcb1-a209ad236447","content":"Use conditional compilation directives in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n#if ANDROID\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();\n#elif IOS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.IosNotificationService>();\n#elif WINDOWS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();\n#endif\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\nEach platform implementation lives under `Platforms/<platform>/` and is only compiled for its target (the folder-based targeting MAUI sets up by default in the `.csproj`).\n\n**Key points:**\n- The `#if` directives ensure only the relevant registration compiles per platform.\n- Place each implementation in its platform folder so it has access to platform APIs.\n- Inject `INotificationService` anywhere via constructor injection — the correct implementation resolves automatically at runtime.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cc6cc8a2-eaa9-4408-9e79-3b67bb3347cd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI dependency injection - specifically how to register platform-specific implementations of an `INotificationService` interface in `MauiProgram.cs`. This is a general knowledge question, not a codebase-specific task.\n\nI'll provide a concise answer showing the standard pattern using conditional compilation or the `OnPlatform` pattern in MAUI DI.","outputTokens":381,"requestId":"7FD5:2F61F4:5DF8416:66E2E25:69F15884"},"id":"3c860aaa-f12b-41e4-ad2e-01a8bc71650f","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:02:05.888Z","parentId":"3364653d-2c59-4621-b9ce-034b5c85935f"}
